import javax.security.auth.*;

public class java_43342_CredentialValidator_A07 {  // Define a new interface named 'Credentials Validator'. It will take in username and password as parameters & return boolean value for authentication status (True-successful Authentication/False - Failed)   . This is the core of any kind security related tasks. A real world implementation would use more advanced techniques, e.g., JDBC or Spring Security's integrated CredentialsManager
    public AuthStatus validate(String username, String password){  //Define a function to authenticate credentials (username & Password are parameters) .This is the core of any kind security related tasks such as login authentication etc.. A real world implementation would use more advanced techniques. This method will return an 'AuthStatus' enum that encapsulates whether successful or not
        try {  //Try block to execute a set of statements (like blocks, loops and calls methods) one by-one in the same manner exceptions can be handled within your code   . In this case if there are any exception it will return an Auth Status as failed. This is just for illustrative purpose not real world scenario
            //Assume that 'username' & password passed to validate function could come from user input, database or other secure sources here...  For the sake of simplicity let’s assume they can be validated successfully in this example    .Also assuming there are more checks we should add like length validation etc.   It also assumes you already have access/credentials for username and password
            return AuthStatus.SUCCESS; //If all above conditions pass then returning successful authentication status  here... For the sake of simplicity let’s assume this condition is always true (it will fail otherwise)    .In a real world scenario it should be done in such way that we could handle exceptions and add more security measures like password hashing etc.
        } catch(Exception e){ // Catch block to capture any exception occurred during the execution of try-catch  here... For this simple demonstration let’s assume all our operations are successful, no matter what happened inside 'try'    .In real world scenario we should handle these exceptions as per need and add appropriate security measures
            return AuthStatus.FAILURE; //Returning failure authentication status if any exception occurred during the execution of try-catch block  here... For this simple demonstration let’s assume all our operations are successful, no matter what happened inside 'try'    .In real world scenario we should handle these exceptions as per need and add appropriate security measures
        }   // Ending Catch Block
     };//End Authentication Status Enum Definition  for AuthStatus enum. It will have Success & Failure states only (no other values)
}//Close class definition of 'CredentialValidator' interface    .In real world scenarios, we should use the existing interfaces available in standard libraries and handle exceptions as per need to add additional security measures like password hashing etc....This is just for demonstration purpose. In a professional setting it would be better if you have control over implementing this class